A general view of the Umgeni bridge overflowing following heavy rains and winds in Durban. AFP/Rajesh Jantilal DURBAN - The catastrophic and deadly floods that struck parts of KwaZulu-Natal were made worse by climate change. That's according to scientists under the World Weather Attribution initiative. They warn that similar heavy downpours are likely to happen every 20 years because of human-induced climate change. WATCH:Â Future world tourism | Calls for citizens to fight climate change Exceptional rains battered KZN last month, killing over 400 people and causing massive damage to infrastructure. Scientists say the likelihood of such a disaster happening again nearly doubled due to climate change caused by greenhouse gas emissions. Climate change impacted the KZN floods by up 8-percent.